<DOC><DOCNO> AP880908-0071 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0635EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-AsiaDisasters     09-08 0311</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Asia Disasters,0322</SECOND><HEAD>Floods, Earthquakes, Storms and Heat Hit Asia</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Bangladesh Floods</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a summary of natural disastersthat have hit Asia since June:      FLOODS:   Aug. 27 _ Floods triggered by annual monsoons claim at least 416lives in Bangladesh and leave more than 21 million people homeless.Newspapers claim more than 1,200 people are killed. At one time,three-fourths of the impoverished nation is under water. Becausewells and pumps are submerged, people begin drinking flood water,prompting a rise in diarrhea cases.      EARTHQUAKES:   Aug. 20 _ An earthquake registering 6.5 on the Richter scalejolts the Himalayan mountains, foothills and plains of India andNepal. It is the deadliest temblor in the region in 30 years. Atleast 714 people are killed in Nepal and 281 in India. The officialtolls are considered understated because the monsoons cut off roadsto many remote villages. Tens of thousands of homes, mostly ofbrick and mud, are destroyed.   Aug. 6 _ An earthquake measuring 7.3 on the Richter scale shakesBurma, Bangladesh, northern India and parts of Pakistan andAfghanistan. Four people die in India.      STORMS:   Aug. 16 _ A storm kills 1,406 people and causes $1.2 billion indamage to the central Chinese province of Shaanxi. It also triggersmountain torrents that destroy 3,000 homes, 14,326 acres offarmland and washes away 165 miles of highway. Officials call itthe most destructive storm in the country's history.   Sept. 2 _ Landslides caused by torrential rains kill at least 35people in various parts of Nepal.      HEAT:   June 4 _ Northern and central India swelter in the worst heat in20 years, with temperatures climbing as high as 117 degrees fornearly three weeks. The government says at least 450 people died,most in the desert state of Rajasthan.</TEXT></DOC>